                 <h2 >Why Roy Hodgson's latest blooper is no surprise to Liverpool fans</h2>
                              <img src="10.jpg" Width="500" Height="300" style="border:thick double #300000"/>

                             <p style="color:white;text-align:left">
                              
 <b>Roy Hodgson's latest comments about Liverpool's training regime are just another blunder in a long list of spoken bloopers from the England manager.</b>
                               <br></br>
                              As if exposing Raheem Sterling's 'tiredness' as an excuse for not starting against Estonia wasn't stupid enough, the former Reds boss has followed it up with questioning Liverpool's training methods under Brendan Rodgers.
                                <br></br>
Liverpool supporters are used to Hodgson's cringe-worthy comments after his term in charge at Anfield.
                              <br></br>
One classic example of Hodgson putting his foot in it while in charge was when the Reds got past Trabzonspor in the Europa League play-off round and he hailed the win as 'a famous European night'.
                             <br></br>
Regarding Daniel Sturridge's injury, Hodgson has now insisted that there is little benefit to be gained from Rodgers' carefully laid plans.
                             <br></br>
'I don't think there is a lot of medical evidence to support the two day recovery,' Hodgson said.
                             <br></br>
Considering the sports science expertise that Rodgers draws upon it will be interesting to see how the Liverpool manager responds.
                             <br></br>
Last season Hodgson riled the Reds when he admitted he had pressured Sturridge into playing against Germany, despite the player being hampered by a thigh problem, because he wanted to 'test his resolve'.
                            <br></br>
That club v country row has since intensified.
                              <br></br>
Hodgson needs Liverpool's support and co-operation with Sterling, Sturridge, Adam Lallana, Jordan Henderson, Rickie Lambert, Glen Johnson and Jon Flanagan all at Anfield.
                             <br></br>
But the England boss is going the wrong way about it if he wants to get Liverpool on side.
                             <br></br>
And with Hodgson vowing to call the Liverpool manager to discuss Sterling's fatigue, the conversation promises to be a lively one.

</p>
                              



